  "doi": "10.1038/s41587-026-03128-x",
  "title": "Deep peptide recognition profiling decodes TCR specificity and enables disease-associated antigen discovery.",
  "journal": "Nature biotechnology",
  "year": 2026,
  "authors": "Wang N, Yeh H, Lai B, Perera J, Jude KM, Risch I, Um J, Chen X, Xiang X, Wang C, Liu LD, Yang X, Paley MA, Khan AA, Garcia KC."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study employs high-throughput yeast display coupled with protein language models to generate deep peptide recognition profiles for HLA-B*27:05-restricted TCRs from patients with ankylosing spondylitis and acute anterior uveitis, revealing that these TCRs recognize their cognate peptides predominantly through CDR3\u03b2 interactions. The trained models achieve superior prediction of T cell activation compared to existing structural prediction tools and identify novel candidate autoantigens relevant to these HLA-B*27:05-associated autoimmune diseases. The work demonstrates that TCR generalization depends on functional rather than sequence-based similarity, establishing a scalable platform for decoding TCR specificity and discovering disease-linked autoantigens\u2014particularly valuable for understanding autoimmune pathology and informing rational TCR engineering approaches.",
